Laptop Pricing

Sean Mitchell

Intro

I chose a dataset titled “Laptop Price” from Kaggle when browsing for sets that I may find compelling.

Link to dataset: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/muhammetvarl/laptop-price

This is a dataset of just over 1,300 individual laptop models with specification details and prices. I searched on Kaggle for “laptops” and selected this dataset because I have always had a passion for technology since a child, especially for consumer electronics like smartphones and laptops. Over the past decade, I have more or less kept up with popular laptop releases, trends, and the overall industry, so I was naturally excited to explore this data.

Laptop Price by Type

I immediately began to explore which factors determine the price of a laptop. I plotted price distributions by type of laptop. There are 6 different equipment types in this dataset. The workstation type has the highest average price, while notebooks and netbooks (which make up over 50% of laptops in the dataset) have the lowest average prices. Another key insight is the high prices of gaming laptops, which have not only a large median, but both outlier laptops with prices over $5,500 belong to the gaming category. The high price of gaming laptops is likely caused by high prices of adequate graphics cards, which are a required component of the gaming laptop category. The type of laptop seems like it affects its price, yet I suspected this correlation because gaming laptops and workstations usually have better and more expensive components than notebooks.

In my “Laptop Price by Type” boxplot visualization, I included details on demand tooltip interactivity to allow users to mouse over individual boxes or points for further understanding. Mousing over a box shows details of the price distribution that users would likely not know immediately after looking at the chart. Mousing over individual points also shows the product and exact price of that point. I felt this was useful for curious users like myself that want to know which products these outliers were exactly.

Laptop Price by RAM

To confirm what I suspected was a more direct correlation, I also plotted the price distribution by laptop RAM specification. The dataset included laptops with memory between 2 and 64 GB, which can be divided into 9 categories. I presented each RAM configuration category in descending order to easily convey the positive correlation between RAM and price. This was expected because the more RAM, the faster and more expensive the hardware.

Laptop Price by Weight

Finally, I plotted laptop price by weight in a scatterplot. It is noticeable that heavier laptops (3.4kg and over) cost more than others; however; there does not seem to be a linear relationship between weight and price. I decided to also analyze how laptop type plays into weight and price with the addition of color to this chart. I used the default tableau10 color scheme because it was easiest on the eyes and each laptop type was distinguishable compared to other Vega color schemes I worked with. With the addition of color, we can now see that gaming laptops are heaviest, which is expected with the large mass of hardware and cooling components required to run modern games on a laptop.

I added filtering interactivity to this chart as well the ability to zoom in or out to allow users to filter specific types of laptops in order to distinguish exactly how each type’s clustering relates to others. After filtering through each type, I understood that while the 2 in 1 Convertible type has the lightest few laptops in the dataset, it is the Ultrabook category with the highest concentration of light laptops, and some 2 in 1 Convertibles are actually quite heavy. On top of zooming and filtering, I also included details on demand tooltips for users to reveal which products make up the points they are interested in mousing over. After exploring this dataset, I now better understand how laptop pricing is correlated with the cost of components, and the intended type of laptop / target consumer can really affect how each product is constructed.
